@NODE edwindow " The Design/Edit Window "
@{B}@{U}
The Design/Edit Window
@{UB}@{UU}

This window is used to enter information about a vampire into Primogen.  It uses
a series of gadgets to allow the entry of data.  The gadgets are as follows:

  Gadget        Description
  ~~~~~~        ~~~~~~~~~~~
  Name          This string gadget allows the entry of a vampire's name.
                You click on this gadget and then type it in.

  Generation    This integer gadget allows the entry of the vampire's generation.

  Clan          This cycle gadget allows the entry of a vampire's clan.
                The default is Brujah.  To change this, click on the gadget
                repeatedly until it cycles over to the desired clan.

  Animalism
      ...       These cycle gadgets represent the status of the disciplines.
  Thaumaturgy   By default the vampire has a rating of 'None' in each discipline,
                however, by clicking on these gadgets, the status of any
                particular discipline can be cycled through the 3 available
                ratings 'None', 'Standard' and 'Superior'.

                For a description of how to tell what a standard or superior
                discipline is consult your @{"Jyhad" link jyhad} rules.


  Accept        This gadget indicates to Primogen you are satisfied with the
                changes you have made.  This window will close and you will be
                returned to the @{"Main Window" link mainwindow}.  If you were adding a
                new vampire it can now be found in your Storage Area.  If you
                were editing an old vampire, it will be be modified to represent
                the new information.

  Merits/Flaws  Pressing this button will open the @{"Merit/Flaw window" link mflawwindow}.

  Cancel        Pressing this button will close the Design/Edit window (losing
                all changes) and return you to the @{"Main Window" link mainwindow}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Mflawwindow " Merit/Flaw Window "
@{B}@{U}
The Merit/Flaw Window
@{UB}@{UU}

This window is used to modify a vampire's merits and flaws.  In Jyhad these are
given as the text of a vampire card.

It was necessary to come up with possible effects these special abilities would
have on the game, and this lead me to devise 8 different @{"strategies" link strategies} for winning
the game.  Every discipline and every special ability has an effect on these
strategies, making them easier or more difficult paths to victory.

As there is a finite number of permutations of disciplines, it was possible to
devise a simple algorithm  to calculate the disciplines' effect on the 8
strategies.  However there are theoretically an infinite number of different 
special abilities, and as such there is no deterministic way of calculating an
arbitrary special ability's effect.

This being the case, it has been left to the human user to determine the effect
any special ability might have on gameplay.

I have already entered each vampire that I own into the database, along with my
estimation of that vampire's special abilities' effects on the strategies.  Each
strategy has a rating from -2 to 5.

A rating of 0 is normal.  Negative ratings are refered to as flaws and positive
ratings are merits.  There are a few hard fast rules, I've devised which will
cover a great many vampires.  These are given in the description of the relevent
@{"strategy" link strategies}.

@ENDNODE


@Node STRATEgies " The Strategies"
@{B}@{U}
The Strategies
@{UB}@{UU}

The 8 Strategies along with any special rules follow:

@{B}@{U}
Offensive
@{UB}@{UU}
This deck is specialized in offensive combat, or at bleeding the opponent.  The
idea is to put as many of your opponents vampires into torpor as possible, by
multiple damage points or agravated damage, and then hit your opponents pool
with multiple bleeds.

Special abilities which give +1 to offensive include:
            - +1 hand damage
            - 2 hand damage
            - +1 Bleed
            - hand damage is treated as agravated
            - pay 1 blood to gain 1 maneuver

@{B}@{U}
Defensive
@{UB}@{UU}
This deck is strong in keeping its minions out of torpor.  Your opponent can't
bleed you if she spends all her efforts just hurting your minions.  Aggravated
damage doesn't scare you because it is easily soaked.  And when your opponent
does manage to bleed you, it doesn't matter because you've always got a card to
reduce bleed handy.

Special abilities include:
            - spend 1 blood to gain 1 dodge
            - change aggravated damage to normal
            - Don't need to tap to block vampires of 3rd gen or less (+2 bonus)

@{B}@{U}
Stealth
@{UB}@{UU}
This deck is strong at doing things without being blocked.  If you opponent
can't get you into a fight, then you dont need to be good at it.  However keep
in mind that occasionally you will need to block an opponent's minions, and
stealth is completely useless for this.

Special abilities include:
            - +1 stealth for any 1 type of action
            - +1 stealth for ALL actions (+2 stealth bonus)


@{B}@{U}
Detection
@{UB}@{UU}
This is the opposite of stealth.  It helps you to prevent your opponent from
taking actions which might otherwise go unblocked.  Detection abilities are
ALWAYS useful.  Many of the more fundamental actions a minion might take, take
place at +1 stealth.  If you can get a +1 intercept bonus, you could for example
block a hungry vampire from feeding (probably sending it into torpor in the
process).  Stop a political action before it starts.  A deck that is strong in
Combat and Detection is a frightening prospect indeed.

Special abilities include:
            - +1 intercept against any 1 type of action or minion.
            - +1 intercept for ALL actions (+2 detection bonus)

@{B}@{U}
Political
@{UB}@{UU}
A political deck should have many political action cards, and if possible
vampires with votes.  Political actions can be used effectively to achieve
almost any game effect.  They can allow you to exert more control over the game.

Special abilities include:
            - Primogen (+1 bonus)
            - Prince   (+2 bonus)
            - Justicar (+3 bonus)

@{B}@{U}
Speed
@{UB}@{UU}
A speed deck has many small vampires, and few large ones.  It relies on
overwhelming your opponent by the sheer number of minions you might throw at
him.
Special abilities include:
            - any ability to put blood on uncontrolled vampires.
            - any ability to increase the size of your hand
            - any ability to discard cards.

@{B}@{U}
Control
@{UB}@{UU}
A control deck is one which allows the methuselah alot of choices over what
happens in the game, and allows the methuselah to deny those choices to others.
A deck with a high control rating will tend to cause your opponent to lose
control of his deck and vice versa.

Special abilities include:
            - any vampires which can take an action which would be illegal
              otherwise. i.e. act out of turn, attack another minion, give blood
              to another controlled minion.
            - any power that help the controller to win contested cards.
            - any power which will deny another kind of vampire a certain kind
              of freedom. i.e.

Control powers are +1 when they only apply to a certain kind of vampire (based
on clan or generation typically).  They are usually +2 when they apply to
everyone.

@{B}@{U}
Knowledge
@{UB}@{UU}
A knowledge deck allows you to have more information, and thus make better
decisions when playing Jyhad.  Methuselahs with a high knowledge rating tend to
know everything, about everyone (at least as far as the game goes).

Special abilities include:
            - any that let you look at cards which you would not otherwise be
              allowed to look at.

@endnode
@node evalwindow " The Evaluation Window"
@NEXT checks
@{B}@{U}
The Evaluation Window
@{UB}@{UU}

This window lists many statistical and calculated results for the current crypt.  
It is updated in real-time as modifications are made to the crypt and may be
left open without interfering with the operation of the @{"main window" link mainwindow}.

It also contains a series of checkmark boxes.  Explained @{"here" link checks}.

The results of the data fields are explained below.

    Field           Description
    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Vampires:       The number of vampires in the Crypt

    Generations:    The sum total of all generations of vampires in the Crypt.

    Clans:          The number of @{I}different@{UI} clans in the crypt.

    Average:        The mean average generation of each vampire in the Crypt.

            
                                     @{B}Disciplines Box@{UB}

    Standard:       The total number of slots of disciplines vampires possess,
                    rated at standard.


    Superior:       The Total number of slots of disciplines vampires possess,
                    rated at Superior

                                       @{B}Totals Box@{UB}

    Quality:        A special weighted total which adds extra emphasis on very
                    high or very low ratings.  This is not an average.  But a
                    calculation of the general quality of disciplines in your
                    crypt.  A deck with many different disciplines will tend to
                    score low here.  A deck with only a few disciplines will
                    tend to score high.  This reflects the reality that a deck
                    which is very strong in a few disciplines has better 
                    chances of succeeding than a deck which is 'average' in 
                    many.  The same rule applies to strategy strengths.

    Strength:       A special weighted total strength of the strategies.  This
                    is not an average, but a calculated final strength which
                    should hold, provided you design your library while keeping
                    your strengths and weaknesses in mind.

                    Typically only choose cards which help your best strengths.
                    Trying to compensate for your crypts weaknesses in your
                    library will most likely result in a fruitless up-hill
                    battle.  The secret to winning at Jyhad is to face your
                    enemy on your own terms, using your best weapons.
                    The same rule applies to disciplines.


@{B}@{U}Strategy Strengths Chart@{UB}@{UU}

This chart shows the calculated strengths of each strategy type based on both
vampire special abilities and the particular strengths and qualities of
disciplines which affect those strategies.  Speed is mostly affected by the
average generation of the vampires in the crypt compared to the 'typical' crypt.

Each other strategy is affected by some combination of discipline and their 
respective quality ratings as well as other factors.  The exact algorithm used
is beyond the scope of this document (for now).

@{B}@{U}Discipline Strengths Chart@{UB}@{UU}

This chart shows the frequency of each discipline in your crypt.

The Weighted column shows a weighted frequency, which values Superior 
disciplines higher than standard disciplines.

The Standard column shows the number of vampires with the discipline at Standard
rating divided by the total number of vampires.

The Superior column shows the number of vampires with the discipline at superior
rating divided by the total number of vampires.

The Quality column shows a special calculated total, which takes into account
the generation of the individual vampires which possess the discipline in
question as well as such issues as Superior and Standard Frequencies, and
weights.  It is this column that gives you the most meaningful information on
the true strengths of the various disciplines in your deck.  In general practice
this is the ONLY column I look at when determining which disciplines to
emphasize in my library.
@endnode
