@{B}
             @{U}Jyhad: If You think its like Magic.  Think Again.@{UU}
                              by David Zvekic
@{UB}
Jyhad is without a doubt one of the most sophisticated tradable card games
on the market.  It requires both wit and careful planning in order to play
a strong and consistent game.

The Jyhad is an ancient and secret war, between the most ancient and
powerful of vampires, the methuselahs.  It is fought for reasons, that are
known only to the methuselahs, by soldiers who often do not even know that
they are all mere pawns, manipulated by these ancient vampires in the
Jyhad.

In the game Jyhad the players play the role of Methuselahs.  As you might
expect their out to win the Jyhad.

Many new players find it tempting to compare Jyhad to another game
'Magic:The Gathering' (henceforth referred to as MTG).  In doing so they
fall into a common trap.  They design an MTG deck using Jyhad cards.

In Jyhad, new cards are drawn from the library as fast as you can play
them, much unlike MTG where only a single new card is drawn each turn.  In
addition there are no killer card combinations in Jyhad.  Not often is a
Jyhad game played, where victory can easily be traced to a single card or 2
that turned the tides of battle.  Victory can only achieved through a
steady and relentless onslaught.  Drawing and playing many cards in a
single turn.  With that in mind, it is likewise very important to keep your
opponent on the defensive.

Here are some tips I have for those finding it difficult to play a strong
game.

Don't let your prey get the Edge.

If your prey has the Edge, he'll only become more and more powerful while
your blood pool diminishes.  Get it away from him.  Even when you know
he'll only take it back again, it is still better than letting him gain the
extra pool each turn.  If you're lucky he'll be succumb to the same
defeatist attitude, that you're only going to take the Edge back from him
and he'll let you keep it.  Keep lots of 'Computer Hacking' cards around.
These cards are one of the most useful in the game.  You spend them like
there's no tommorow, and they immedietly get replaced.  If only 1 in 5 go
unblocked thats 1 extra point of bleed that didn't cost you anything.

Don't save, discard!.

While in MTG, discarding is a scary thing, in Jyhad discarding is good for
you.  Discarding lets you replace your least useful card with something
that is probably better.  You should take advantage of your discard phase
the moment you have a card you don't see yourself being able to use within
the next turn or 2.  Likewise, don't be cheap with the extra bleed cards,
extra damage, or damage prevention cards.  Use them, even when your
vampires have plenty of blood left and you believe they can soak the
damage.  You'll get more, and if the card you draw to replace them with
isn't useful in this fight, it will be useful outside of combat.

Wake with Evening's Freshness

Put a few 'Wake with Evening's Freshness', or 'Rats Warning' cards in your
deck and use them.  Put many in fact.  If your predator believes that you
have these ready, he may think twice about assuming you can't defend
yourself.  Moreover if you have many of these, you might be able to take
the Edge knowing that you can still respond to bleeds attempts afterwards.
'Cat's Guidance' is also useful for keeping your blockers available.

Act with a Purpose.

Design your deck with a specific purpose and keep to it.  If your deck is
designed for high damage in combat, then stick to this.  Take only those
cards that let you put your enemies minion's into torpor.  Do not be
tempted to make a deck that can handle any situation.  If you keep in mind
that winning the game requires many turns of continual pressure, you will
see that it is not important to be able to deal with every kind of threat.
If your deck is poor politically, then put your opponents Primogen's and
Princes into torpor to balance the playing field.  Even better, be on your
prey's case so hard that he doesn't call a vote for fear of letting you
slip in a multi point bleed when he leaves too many minions tapped.

If your deck is a political deck, then vote your prey to death.  Commit
diablerie often and with vigour, as you can probably overturn any calls for
a blood hunt.  Don't miss the opportunity to take your opponents minions
right out of the game.  Use 'Political Backlash' to punish any that try to
call a Blood Hunt.  Keep in mind that you can't play Reaction cards during
your turn so this tactic only works if you diablerize during someone elses.
Amaranth is useful for this, as is any card that will let you intercept a
vampire trying to recover from torpor.

With a political deck you can also let people bleed you, and then get
revenge with 'Domain Challenge'.  Finally always remember that Political
Action cards can also be used as votes, and that you'll get replacements
soon enough so spend, spend, spend!

Try to concentrate on only a few disciplines.  This way you'll always be
able to play the cards you've got in your hand.  Also don't underestimate
'Master:Skill' cards.  They make a huge difference, in a well designed deck
with only a few disciplines.

Speed

In Jyhad your cards are typically replaced immedietly.  The consequence of
this is that you want to be able to use all of your cards as soon as you
draw them.  If a card isn't immedietly useful, discard it, and think twice
about even including it in your library in the future.

Another note on speed.  Cheap vampires, are better than expensive ones.  In
my crypt over 1/2 of my vampires are 2nd generation or LESS!  If you don't
have enough minions in play, then your entire game suffers.  Your deck
plays slower and you'll lose the Edge.  If most of your vampires are small
and cheap, you'll naturally work your way through your crypt and get at the
powerhouses soon enough.  With 'Master:Skill' cards your cheap vampires can
use the disciplines just as well as vampires that take several times more
blood to get into play.

Contested Cards.

Many people use contested cards the wrong way.  In a multiplayer game you
should almost never contest someone's card unless that methuselah is so low
on pool they will be forced to yield very soon.  If they don't yield, you
both waste blood while all the other players get stronger.  When you are
winning the game, it is a good time to contest cards.  If you are losing
the game you should seriously consider yielding as you are in no position
to throw away the blood pool.  If you aren't prepared to go the full
distance in a contest, then it's probably better to yield.

Avoid conflict.

In a multiplayer game, your predator is probably very leery of tapping all
of his vampires.  If it looks like he will be satisfied by gaining control
of the Edge, then he'll probably stop bleed attempts as soon as he gets the
Edge.  You may want to simply allow his first minion to bleed you, instead
of blocking it.  If you don't have the Edge, 1 pool is a small price to
pay, to save your minions from slaughter.

Winning is Everything

While some may say "the most important thing is to have fun." We all know
that the best way to have fun is to win!  Hopefully, these tips will help
you to formulate a stronger playing strategy, and win more games.  If you
happen to have fun along the way, well hey, fun is good too!


The Author: David Zvekic is a computer science student at York University,
and author of the soon to be released PRIMOGEN shareware Jyhad deck 
analysis tool.  His internet email address is:  cs922097@ariel.cs.yorku.ca

