@NODE ToolTypes "Primogen Tool Types
@{B}@{U}
Icon Tool Types
@{UB}@{UU}

A number of Tool types are supported by Primogen.  In all cases where there is a
tool type, an equivalent command line parameter is supported, and is described
along with the tool type below.  You can change the tool types by clicking on
the Primogen icon and selecting 'Information...' from the 'Icons' menu in
Workbench.  See your Workbench manuals.

The purpose of these tool types is to let you change the way primogen calculates
its Discipline Qualities.  The only reason to do this is if you disagree with
my subjective oppinion on the subject.


@{B}
SHIFT=#@{UB}

Usage:
 Where # is the Generation Shift Index.
 A low shift index (0-2) favours low generation vampires more while a high shift
 index (greater than 2) favours low generation vampires less.

 This works as follows.  When comparing vampires the shift index is always added
 as a constant.  If the Shift index where 0 then a 10th Generation vampire would
 be considered 10 times older than a 1st generation vampire.  If the shift index
 where 10 then a 10th Generation vampire would only appear to be slighty less
 than twice as old (as 10+10 = 20 and 1+10 = 11.  20 is slightly less than twice
 of 11).

 This value is used when calculating Discipline values, as a discipline is
 considered more valuable on a young vampire than on an old one.  Young vampires
 tend to get into play while old vampires cost so much blood that they often
 don't get used or take a long time to put out.

    CLI Usage:  Primogen -shift #

 Default Shift Index is 2.0.

@{B}
BASE=#@{UB}

Usage:
 Where # is the Base Blood Index.
 This indicates the Generation which you consider to be NORMAL.  Vampires are
 considered either 'young' or 'old' based on this Base Generation

    ClI Usage:  Primogen -base #

 Default Base Generation is 4.0. @{"Here" link basegenwhy} is why.

@{B}
WEIGHT=#@{UB}

Usage:
 Where # is the Superior/Standard weight Index.
 All superior rated disciplines are multiplied by this number, to determine
 their value while all standard disciplines are divided by this number.

 If you wanted to get perverse you could put a value less than 1 here and
 standard disciplines would be considered more valuable than superior.  If you
 wanted to be REALLY perverse you can put a value of 0 here.  (I don't suggest
 trying it.  I only mention it, as an illustration of something you should
 not do.)  If your system crashes consider that a "feature" of Primogen.

    CLI Usage: Primogen -weight #

 Default Superior/Standard Weight Index is 1.25

@{B}@{U}
Complete CLI Example@{UB}@{UU}

    primogen -weight 1.25 -Base 4.5 -shift 2.0



@ENDNODE
@NODE basegenwhy " Why is 4th Generation so special?"
@{B}@{U}
Why is 4th Generation so Special?
@{UB}@{UU}

The reason for this is fairly straightforward.  I used to believe that 5.5
should be the base generation.  This number was fairly arbitrary, but I felt it
had some logic behind it as 1/2 the generations are less than 5.5 and 1/2 of
them are greater.  It seemed sensible.  However while walking home one day it
suddenly dawned upon me.

Every turn there are 4 transfers.  The largest vampire one could possibly bring
out in 1 turn is 4th gen.  And there you have my justification.  Any vampire
higher than 4th gen takes at least 2 turns to get into play, and will slow down
your deck.  Vampires of 4th gen are 'normal' (taking 1 turn) and vampires of
younger than 4th gen are 'fast' (allowing you to get multiple vampires into play
during the same turn).

@ENDNODE
@NODE checks "The checkboxes"
@{B}@{U}
What are these Check Boxes.
@{UB}@{UU}

The Check Marks are there for you to tell Primogen which disciplines you intend
to use.  Primogen then uses these disciplines to accurately calculate a Total
quality in the Totals Box.  As you build your crypt and play with the check
boxes you will soon see that making a cypt that is strong at more than 2 or 3
disciplines is difficult (if not impossible).

The Strategy Strengths are affected by which disciplines you put in your
crypt, as you will see the ratings are highest when you use many disciplines.
This is because any discipline you do not choose to use is considered to be
rated at 0 for the purpose of determining how it affects your strategy
strengths.  Obviously if you don't put any celerity cards in your library, your
effecting rating in celerity is 0 regardless how many vampires may have
celerity.

Don't fall into the trap of using too many disciplines to boot the total
strength rating.  Total quality is equaly important, and a wise player knows the
proper balance.

If you are only using version 2.x of the OS the checkboxes may look the wrong
size.  It's time to upgrade to 3.x or higher.  In version 2.x checkmark gadgets
are not scalable.
@ENDNODE
@NODE requirements "What do you need to use Primogen?"
@{B}@{U}
The Requirements
@{UB}@{UU}

Primogen requires an Amiga using version 2.0 or higher of the Operating System.

Primogen doesn't require an FPU although it does use floating point math and will 
exploit an FPU if there is one present.

If you are using version 3.x of Amigados Primogen looks nicer, and obeys the user
preferences better.

1.3 users are out of luck as I used Gadtools.library.  Time to upgrade!
@ENDNODE



